1 Sec. 5. 32 MRSA §13857, sub-§2, ¶C, as enacted by PL 2003, c. 542, §1, is
2 amended to read:
3 C. An Notwithstanding Title 10, section 8003-H, an applicant who is licensed in good
4 standing at the time of application to the board under the laws of a jurisdiction that has
5 not entered into a reciprocal agreement and who does not meet the requirements of
6 paragraph B may qualify for licensure by submitting evidence satisfactory to the board
7 that the applicant's qualifications for licensure are substantially similar to those
8 requirements in this chapter. applicant:
9 (1) Has held for at least 2 years a license issued by a board in another jurisdiction
10 for an occupation with a similar scope of practice to the practice governed by this
11 chapter; and
12 (2) Does not have a complaint, allegation or investigation pending before a board
13 in another jurisdiction that relates to unprofessional conduct or a crime or a
14 violation of an applicable ethics code or standard of practice.
15 The department shall post the information in this paragraph on its publicly accessible
16 website. The words or similar words: "If you are licensed in another state or country"
17 must be included in the post.
18 Sec. 6. 32 MRSA §13858, first ¶, as amended by PL 2007, c. 402, Pt. EE, §5, is
19 further amended to read:
20 To Except as otherwise provided in section 13857, subsection 2, paragraph C, to be
21 eligible for a license to practice counseling at any level, an applicant must be at least 18
22 years of age and satisfactorily pass any examination as the board may prescribe by its rules.
23 Each applicant must demonstrate trustworthiness and competence to engage in the practice
24 of counseling in such a manner as to safeguard the interests of the public. Each applicant
25 must submit an application and pay the fee as set under section 13859. The license
26 categories "licensed clinical professional counselor," "licensed pastoral counselor" and
27 "licensed marriage and family therapist" are of equivalent clinical status. Clinical status
28 grants the ability to diagnose and treat mental health disorders.
29 Sec. 7. 32 MRSA §13858, 2nd ¶, as enacted by PL 1989, c. 465, §3, is amended
30 to read:
31 The Except as otherwise provided in section 13857, subsection 2, paragraph C, the
32 following shall must be considered as minimum evidence satisfactory to the board that an
33 applicant is qualified for licensure under this chapter.
34 SUMMARY
3355 This bill amends the laws governing the licensure of professional counselors, clinical
3366 professional counselors, marriage and family therapists and pastoral counselors to
3377 authorize licensure in this State for an applicant who has held for at least 2 years a license
3388 issued by another jurisdiction for an occupation with a similar scope of practice and who
3399 does not have a complaint, allegation or investigation pending before a board in another
4400 jurisdiction or a violation of an applicable ethics code or standard of practice.
41 The bill also makes the same changes to the law governing the licensure of social
42 workers.
